@node Clipboard conversion
@section Clipboard conversion

@findex markdown-mode-extras-org-paste-dwim
The command @code{markdown-mode-extras-org-paste-dwim} converts clipboard
content between Org and Markdown based on the current major mode.  In
a @samp{markdown-mode} buffer it assumes the clipboard holds Org syntax and
converts to Markdown; in an @samp{org-mode} buffer it does the reverse.
The conversion is performed by piping the system clipboard (@samp{pbv} on
macOS, @samp{xclip} elsewhere) through Pandoc with @samp{--wrap=none}.  A few
post-processing cleanups are applied to the Pandoc output before
yanking.

@findex markdown-mode-extras-paste-with-conversion
When you copy formatted text from a web page or other rich-text
source, @code{markdown-mode-extras-paste-with-conversion} converts the
clipboard to GitHub-Flavored Markdown (@samp{gfm-raw_html}) and inserts the
result.  It uses @code{simple-extras-pandoc-convert} from @samp{simple-extras.el}
to detect whether the clipboard contains HTML or Org and to choose the
appropriate Pandoc input format.  For the reverse process (copying
Markdown as formatted HTML), see @code{ox-clip-formatted-copy}.

@node Section operations
@section Section operations

@findex markdown-mode-extras-copy-section
The command @code{markdown-mode-extras-copy-section} copies the body of the
Markdown section at point to the kill ring and echoes it.  A ``section''
is the text between a heading (@samp{^#+ ...}) and the next heading of the
same or higher level.  If called with a non-nil SECTION argument
(available only from Lisp), the command searches for the named section
instead of using the one at point.

Internally, the command calls @code{markdown-mode-extras-get-section}
(@ref{Getting section content}).

@node Link editing
@section Link editing

@findex markdown-mode-extras-remove-url-in-link
When editing a Markdown document you sometimes want to unlink text
while keeping the description.  The command
@code{markdown-mode-extras-remove-url-in-link} does exactly that: with
point inside a Markdown link (@samp{[description](url)}), it removes the
link markup and leaves only the description text.

With a prefix argument, the command instead prompts for a @emph{new} URL
and re-inserts the link with the original description and the
replacement URL@.  This is handy for updating broken or outdated links.

The command uses @code{markdown-mode-extras-delete-link}
(@ref{Deleting a link}) to remove the original link structure.

